WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.295 --> 00:00:01.595
Here in small-town Norway,

00:00:01.595 --> 00:00:04.128
Christmas is celebrated
with a unique intimacy

00:00:04.128 --> 00:00:07.161
and a Scandinavian flair
for community.

00:00:07.161 --> 00:00:10.328
We're in Drobak,
about an hour south of Oslo.

00:00:10.328 --> 00:00:13.161
While it's Norway's
self-proclaimed

00:00:13.161 --> 00:00:13.928
capital of Christmas,

00:00:13.928 --> 00:00:18.994
Drobak feels like any idyllic
town on a fjord.

00:00:18.994 --> 00:00:21.361
It's Santa Lucia day,
December 13th,

00:00:21.361 --> 00:00:24.616
one of the darkest days of
winter and an important

00:00:24.641 --> 00:00:27.361
part of the Scandinavian
Christmas season.

00:00:27.361 --> 00:00:30.728
All over nordic Europe, little
candle-bearing Santa Lucias

00:00:30.728 --> 00:00:33.328
are bringing light
to the middle of winter

00:00:33.328 --> 00:00:36.761
and the promise
of the return of summer.

00:00:36.761 --> 00:00:39.228
These processions are led
by a young Lucia

00:00:39.228 --> 00:00:40.861
wearing a crown
of lights.

00:00:40.861 --> 00:00:44.495
[ Children singing
"Santa Lucia" in Norwegian ]

00:00:49.228 --> 00:00:52.961
♪ ...Santa Lucia ♪

00:00:52.961 --> 00:00:56.861
♪ Santa Lucia ♪♪

00:00:56.861 --> 00:00:57.728
[ Applause ]

00:00:57.728 --> 00:00:59.528
This home has housed
widows and seniors

00:00:59.528 --> 00:01:02.861
for over 200 years, and
today the kindergarteners

00:01:02.861 --> 00:01:07.028
are bringing on the light
in more ways than one.

00:01:07.028 --> 00:01:08.928
The children have baked
the traditional

00:01:08.928 --> 00:01:10.128
Santa Lucia
saffron buns --

00:01:10.128 --> 00:01:12.295
the same ones
these seniors baked

00:01:12.295 --> 00:01:14.628
when they
were kindergarteners.

00:01:14.628 --> 00:01:16.894
Taking their cue
from Santa Lucia,

00:01:16.894 --> 00:01:18.662
Norwegians,
cozy in their homes,

00:01:18.662 --> 00:01:21.395
brighten their long,
dark winters

00:01:21.395 --> 00:01:22.428
with lots of candles,

00:01:22.428 --> 00:01:25.528
white lights -- you'll
never see a colored one--

00:01:25.528 --> 00:01:28.495
and lots of greenery.

00:01:28.495 --> 00:01:30.628
In Norway,
as in the rest of Europe,

00:01:30.628 --> 00:01:33.061
pagan symbols --
like the evergreen tree --

00:01:33.061 --> 00:01:36.095
survive disguised
as Christmas traditions.

00:01:36.095 --> 00:01:39.495
The same is true
with this sprig of mistletoe.

00:01:39.495 --> 00:01:40.028
In Scandinavia,

00:01:40.028 --> 00:01:42.695
it's associated with
the Viking Goddess of love.

00:01:42.695 --> 00:01:44.695
For Celtic people,
it was a sacred plant.

00:01:44.695 --> 00:01:47.428
They used it to heal the sick
and enhance fertility.

00:01:47.428 --> 00:01:50.228
For most of us,
it's just a handy excuse

00:01:50.228 --> 00:01:52.128
to steal
a little Christmas kiss.

00:01:52.128 --> 00:01:55.528
Oh, that's a mistletoe.
Mmmm.

00:01:55.528 --> 00:01:57.328
The Norwegian spirit
of Christmas

00:01:57.328 --> 00:01:59.195
extends even
to the departed.

00:01:59.195 --> 00:02:00.961
Candles flicker
in graveyards

00:02:00.961 --> 00:02:03.928
as families remember
lost loved ones.

00:02:03.928 --> 00:02:04.894
And all over Norway,

00:02:04.894 --> 00:02:07.728
communities gather together
in churches just like this

00:02:07.728 --> 00:02:11.328
as choirs cap Santa Lucia Day
with a concert.

00:02:11.328 --> 00:02:14.462
[ Choir singing
"Angels We Have Heard on High" ]

00:02:14.462 --> 00:02:20.528
♪ ...Glo...ria... ♪

00:02:20.528 --> 00:02:29.994
♪ In excelsis deo ♪♪

00:02:29.994 --> 00:02:34.361
And as the congregation
follows the Santa Lucias out,

00:02:34.361 --> 00:02:35.395
more light of Christmas

00:02:35.395 --> 00:02:38.395
spills into this little
fjord-side community.

00:02:38.395 --> 00:02:42.595
[ Choir singing
"Santa Lucia" in Norwegian ]

00:03:02.861 --> 00:03:05.894
♪ ...Santa Lucia ♪

00:03:05.894 --> 00:03:09.295
♪ Santa Lucia ♪♪

00:03:09.295 --> 00:03:11.994
Christmases everywhere
come with special meals.

00:03:11.994 --> 00:03:15.662
Here in Norway, families treat
children to a rice porridge

00:03:15.662 --> 00:03:19.495
and it comes
with a hidden almond.

00:03:19.495 --> 00:03:24.128
[ Girl exclaiming
in Norwegian ]

00:03:24.128 --> 00:03:27.128
The child who discovers it
wins...

00:03:27.128 --> 00:03:28.462
A marzipan pig!

00:03:28.462 --> 00:03:29.994
It's reminiscent
of the old days

00:03:29.994 --> 00:03:32.728
when a peasant family's
wealth was tied up

00:03:32.728 --> 00:03:34.761
in its precious pig.

00:03:34.761 --> 00:03:37.395
[ Talking, laughing ]

00:03:40.695 --> 00:03:43.761
"Jule ol" or Christmas beer
goes back to medieval times

00:03:43.761 --> 00:03:47.095
when the Vikings liked to
celebrate the winter solstice

00:03:47.095 --> 00:03:49.695
with a particularly
stout brew.

00:03:49.695 --> 00:03:51.428
And holiday desserts
are a big part

00:03:51.428 --> 00:03:53.161
of Norway's
Christmas season:

00:03:53.161 --> 00:03:55.794
The local Christmas fruitcake
called "julekaka"

00:03:55.794 --> 00:04:00.061
and a towering
marzipan "kransekake."

00:04:01.528 --> 00:04:04.861
A common theme across cultures
is a legendary gift giver --

00:04:04.861 --> 00:04:08.662
not always fat and jolly --
who kids butter up with treats.

00:04:08.662 --> 00:04:12.128
While I grew up leaving
Santa Claus milk and cookies

00:04:12.128 --> 00:04:12.928
by the fireplace,

00:04:12.928 --> 00:04:16.794
the kids here leave a bowl
of porridge out by the barn

00:04:16.794 --> 00:04:18.195
for the "julenisse."

00:04:18.195 --> 00:04:20.695
These mischievous
elves-from-the-forest

00:04:20.695 --> 00:04:22.761
visit each Christmas,
not on reindeer,

00:04:22.761 --> 00:04:25.961
but with a horse, pig,
and mouse entourage

00:04:25.961 --> 00:04:27.928
and a bag of gifts.

00:04:27.928 --> 00:04:28.628
Every good child knows

00:04:28.628 --> 00:04:33.328
the "julenisse" is coming
with an exciting reward.

00:04:33.328 --> 00:04:35.728
Just up the fjord,
Norway's capital, Oslo,

00:04:35.728 --> 00:04:39.662
celebrates Christmas
with a more urban charm.

00:04:40.395 --> 00:04:41.662
Streets are decorated,

00:04:41.662 --> 00:04:44.528
locals not ready to rely
on the "julenisse,"

00:04:44.528 --> 00:04:46.495
are out shopping,

00:04:46.495 --> 00:04:49.195
and good cheer
is abundant.

00:04:49.195 --> 00:04:50.728
[ Shrieking ]

00:04:50.728 --> 00:04:52.662
Christmas in Oslo
feels low-key.

00:04:52.662 --> 00:04:55.961
You'll find it best not on
the streets or in the malls,

00:04:55.961 --> 00:05:02.095
but in the homes,
with friends and in music.

00:05:02.095 --> 00:05:05.161
Youthful voices fill
the city's oldest church.

00:05:05.161 --> 00:05:06.361
The old Aker Church,

00:05:06.361 --> 00:05:08.161
which dates back
to the 12th century,

00:05:08.161 --> 00:05:10.894
hosts the
Norwegian Girls' Choir

00:05:10.894 --> 00:05:11.928
for an advent concert.

00:05:13.376 --> 00:05:18.009
[ Choir singing "Personent Hodie"
in Latin ]

